1
00:00:00,942 --> 00:00:28,722
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sama Sambuddhasa

2
00:00:29,309 --> 00:00:36,779
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,798 --> 00:00:48,014
There's a very famous discourse that people always quote to express the non-dogmatic way that the Buddha taught.

4
00:00:49,676 --> 00:00:54,101
And it's known as the Kalama Sutta, the discourses to the Kalamas.

5
00:00:55,582 --> 00:00:59,008
And the question, of course, is how do we know something is true?

6
00:01:01,250 --> 00:01:08,140
So here's a time where all sorts of gurus and ideas are coming forward.

7
00:01:08,180 --> 00:01:11,444
It's quite an exciting little time, really.

8
00:01:12,245 --> 00:01:17,451
And you're living in a town, a small town, and only a few thousand inhabitants.

9
00:01:18,052 --> 00:01:20,977
And these gurus keep turning up and telling you what for.

10
00:01:21,697 --> 00:01:25,522
And they're all saying slightly different things, and of course...

11
00:01:25,790 --> 00:01:27,432
saying everybody else is absolutely useless.

12
00:01:28,213 --> 00:01:29,474
And so you're stuck.

13
00:01:29,495 --> 00:01:31,477
You wonder, well, who's right and who's wrong?

14
00:01:32,659 --> 00:01:43,936
So if you think of these days, somebody, say, who's been brought up in a non-religious family suddenly becomes interested in the religious field and goes out in search.

15
00:01:43,956 --> 00:01:45,298
I mean, it's colossal, isn't it?

16
00:01:45,698 --> 00:01:46,921
I mean, where will you start?

17
00:01:49,144 --> 00:01:55,272
So this is, in a slightly lesser degree, this is the situation of the Kalamas.

18
00:01:55,540 --> 00:01:56,760
He's very modern in a way.

19
00:01:57,621 --> 00:02:01,807
So I'll just read it through so you get the feel of the discourse.

20
00:02:01,826 --> 00:02:07,373
And then say one or two things and then continue next week.

21
00:02:07,393 --> 00:02:08,274
Thus have I heard.

22
00:02:08,514 --> 00:02:13,058
So remember all these scriptures were related by Ananda, his assistant.

23
00:02:13,079 --> 00:02:13,939
Remembered by him.

24
00:02:14,901 --> 00:02:17,944
And he had to repeat them all at this meeting.

25
00:02:19,205 --> 00:02:23,691
On one occasion the Blessed One was wandering on tour with a large sangha of monks.

26
00:02:24,413 --> 00:02:27,436
when he arrived at the town of the Kalamas called Kesaputta.

27
00:02:28,377 --> 00:02:30,479
Now the Kalamas of Kesaputta had heard.

28
00:02:31,240 --> 00:02:38,447
It is said that the ascetic Gautama, the Sakyan son who went forth from the Sakyan family, has arrived at Kesaputta.

29
00:02:39,127 --> 00:02:52,479
Now a good report about that master Gautama has been circulating thus, that the blessed one is an Arahant, perfectly enlightened, accomplished in true knowledge and conduct, fortunate, knower of the world,

30
00:02:52,865 --> 00:03:00,816
unsurpassed leader of persons to be tamed, teacher of devas and humans, the enlightened one, the blessed one.

31
00:03:00,836 --> 00:03:13,292
And having realized, with his own direct knowledge, this world, with its devas, mara and brahma, this population, with its ascetics and brahmins, with its devas and humans, he makes it known to others.

32
00:03:13,712 --> 00:03:21,622
And he teaches a dharma that is good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, with the right meaning and expressions,

33
00:03:21,973 --> 00:03:26,718
He reveals a spiritual life that is perfectly complete and purified.

34
00:03:27,659 --> 00:03:31,525
Now it's good to see such a house.

35
00:03:31,544 --> 00:03:34,187
Then the Kalamas of Kesaputta approached the Blessed One.

36
00:03:35,269 --> 00:03:38,111
Some paid homage to him and sat down to one side.

37
00:03:38,712 --> 00:03:44,378
Some exchanged greetings with him and after greeting and cordial talk sat down to one side.

38
00:03:44,419 --> 00:03:50,765
Some saluted him reverentially and sat down to one side and some remained silent

39
00:03:50,998 --> 00:03:52,722
and sat down to one side.

40
00:03:52,741 --> 00:04:06,602
And the Kalama said to the Blessed One, Venerable Sir, some ascetics and Brahmins who come to Kesaputta explain and elucidate their own doctrines, but disparage, debunk, revile and vilify the doctrines of others.

41
00:04:08,163 --> 00:04:18,879
But then some other ascetics and Brahmins come to Kesaputta and they too explain and elucidate their doctrines, but disparage, debunk, revile and vilify the doctrines of the others.

42
00:04:19,619 --> 00:04:26,446
For us, venerable sir, there is perplexity and doubt as to which of these good ascetics speaks truth and which speaks falsehood.

43
00:04:28,228 --> 00:04:31,050
It is fitting for you to be perplexed, O Kalamas.

44
00:04:31,110 --> 00:04:32,791
It is fitting for you to be in doubt.

45
00:04:33,052 --> 00:04:35,634
Doubt has arisen in you about a perplexing matter.

46
00:04:36,555 --> 00:04:40,240
Come, Kalamas, do not go by oral tradition.

47
00:04:40,300 --> 00:04:42,562
So this is the bit that's always quoted.

48
00:04:43,322 --> 00:04:49,069
Do not go by oral tradition, by lineage of teaching, by hearsay,

49
00:04:49,723 --> 00:05:19,377
by a collection of texts by logic by inferential reasoning by reasoned cogitation by the acceptance of a view after pondering it by the seeming competence of a speaker or because you think the ascetic is our teacher but when you know for yourselves these things are unwholesome these things are blameable these things are censured by the wise

50
00:05:19,745 --> 00:05:25,189
These things, if undertaken in practice, lead to harm and suffering, then you should abandon them.

51
00:05:26,531 --> 00:05:27,793
Now what do you think, Kalamas?

52
00:05:28,632 --> 00:05:33,978
When greed, hatred and delusion arise in a person, is it for his welfare or harm?

53
00:05:34,579 --> 00:05:35,920
For his harm, Venerable Sir.

54
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:48,672
Kalamas, a person who is greedy, hating and deluded, overpowered by greed, hatred and delusion, his thoughts, controlled by them, will destroy life, take what's not given,

55
00:05:49,040 --> 00:05:51,942
Engage in sexual misconduct and tell lies.

56
00:05:52,444 --> 00:05:54,725
He will also prompt others to do likewise.

57
00:05:55,586 --> 00:06:04,156
Will that conduct be to his harm and suffering for a long time?

58
00:06:04,216 --> 00:06:05,757
Yes, Venerable Sir.

59
00:06:07,399 --> 00:06:09,742
Now what do you think, Kalamas?

60
00:06:09,762 --> 00:06:11,524
Are these things wholesome or unwholesome?

61
00:06:12,105 --> 00:06:13,286
Unwholesome, Venerable Sir.

62
00:06:14,086 --> 00:06:15,468
Blameable or blameless?

63
00:06:16,069 --> 00:06:17,511
Blameable, Venerable Sir.

64
00:06:18,031 --> 00:06:20,134
Censured or practiced by the wise?

65
00:06:20,814 --> 00:06:22,778
Censured, venerable sir.

66
00:06:22,798 --> 00:06:26,964
Undertaken and practiced, do they lead to harm and suffering or not?

67
00:06:28,047 --> 00:06:29,309
Or how is it in this case?

68
00:06:29,930 --> 00:06:35,218
Undertaken and practiced, these things lead to harm and suffering, so it appears to us in this case.

69
00:06:35,939 --> 00:06:41,187
It is for this reason, Kalamas, that we said, do not go by oral traditions.

70
00:06:45,031 --> 00:06:45,992
I'm going to repeat that.

71
00:06:46,432 --> 00:06:52,601
Remember, this is the oral tradition, so it's put in a very repetitious way so people can remember it.

72
00:06:54,423 --> 00:06:56,286
Now he said, now he goes on to the opposite.

73
00:06:56,766 --> 00:06:58,009
So what do you think Kalama is?

74
00:06:58,088 --> 00:07:03,836
When non-greed, non-hatred and non-delusion arise in a person, is it for his welfare or harm?

75
00:07:04,098 --> 00:07:05,720
For his welfare, venerable sir.

76
00:07:06,661 --> 00:07:14,312
Kalama is a person who is without greed, without hatred, without delusion, not overpowered by greed and hatred and delusion,

77
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:24,533
His thoughts not controlled by them will abstain from the destruction of life, from taking what is not given, from sexual misconduct and from false speech.

78
00:07:25,173 --> 00:07:27,516
He will also prompt others to do likewise.

79
00:07:28,319 --> 00:07:31,382
Will that conduce to his welfare and happiness for a long time?

80
00:07:31,923 --> 00:07:32,904
Yes, Venerable Sir.

81
00:07:34,026 --> 00:07:35,107
What do you think, Kalamas?

82
00:07:35,988 --> 00:07:37,711
Are these things wholesome or unwholesome?

83
00:07:38,211 --> 00:07:39,213
Wholesome, Venerable Sir.

84
00:07:39,733 --> 00:07:41,154
Blameable or blameless?

85
00:07:41,456 --> 00:07:43,117
Blameless, Venerable Sir.

86
00:07:43,654 --> 00:07:45,858
Censured or praised by the wise.

87
00:07:46,098 --> 00:07:47,360
Praised, venerable sir.

88
00:07:49,281 --> 00:07:52,966
Undertaken and practiced, do they lead to welfare and happiness or not?

89
00:07:53,206 --> 00:07:54,408
Or how is it in this case?

90
00:07:55,129 --> 00:07:58,653
Undertaken and practiced, these things lead to welfare and happiness.

91
00:07:59,233 --> 00:08:00,795
So it appears to us in this case.

92
00:08:01,776 --> 00:08:09,086
It is for this reason, Kalamas, that I said, do not go upon tradition, and so forth.

93
00:08:09,107 --> 00:08:11,889
And then...

94
00:08:12,612 --> 00:08:13,773
He gives them this practice.

95
00:08:15,153 --> 00:08:28,887
Then Kalama is that noble disciple, devoid of covetousness, devoid of ill will, unconfused, clearly comprehending and ever mindful, dwells pervading one quarter with a mind imbued with loving kindness.

96
00:08:29,869 --> 00:08:32,150
Likewise the second, the third and the fourth.

97
00:08:32,811 --> 00:08:39,597
Thus above, below and across and everywhere and to all as to himself he dwells pervading the entire world

98
00:08:39,950 --> 00:08:48,743
with a mind imbued with loving kindness, vast, exalted, measureless, without hostility and without ill will.

99
00:08:49,703 --> 00:08:57,394
And this he says also of compassion, altruistic joy and equanimity.

100
00:08:59,558 --> 00:09:09,432
When Kalama, this noble disciple, has thus made his mind free of enmity, free of ill will, uncorrupted and pure, he has won the four assurances in this very life.

101
00:09:10,274 --> 00:09:38,644
the first assurance he has won is this if there is another world and if good and bad deeds bear fruit and yield results it is possible that on the breakup of the body after death I shall arise in a good destination in a heavenly world the second assurance he has won is this if there is no other world and if good and bad deeds do not bear fruit and yield results still

102
00:09:39,350 --> 00:09:43,996
Right here in this very life, I live happily, free of enmity and ill will.

103
00:09:45,620 --> 00:09:47,522
The third assurance he has won is this.

104
00:09:48,023 --> 00:09:50,706
Suppose evil befalls the evildoer.

105
00:09:51,388 --> 00:09:58,438
Then, as I do not intend evil for anyone, how can suffering affect me, one who does no evil deed?

106
00:09:59,921 --> 00:10:01,844
The fourth assurance he has won is this.

107
00:10:02,666 --> 00:10:05,610
Suppose evil does not befall an evildoer.

108
00:10:05,995 --> 00:10:11,020
then right here I see myself purified in both respects.

109
00:10:11,041 --> 00:10:21,052
When Kalamas, this noble disciple, has thus made his mind free of enmity, free of ill will, uncorrupted and pure, he has won these four assurances in this very life.

110
00:10:22,394 --> 00:10:34,888
So it is, blessed one, so it is, fortunate one, when this noble disciple has thus made his mind free of enmity, free of ill will, uncorrupted and pure, he has won these four assurances in this very life.

111
00:10:35,273 --> 00:10:36,815
And then the usual P in at the end.

112
00:10:37,375 --> 00:10:57,965
Magnificent Venerable Sir, Magnificent Venerable Sir, the Blessed One has made the Dharma clear in many ways, as though he were turning upright what had been overthrown, revealing what had been hidden, showing the way to one who was lost, or holding up a lamp in the darkness to those with good eyesight can see forms.

113
00:10:58,927 --> 00:11:04,875
So now we go for refuge to the Blessed One, to the Dharma and to the Sangha of Monks.

114
00:11:05,176 --> 00:11:12,225
Let the Blessed One accept us as lay followers who have gone to refuge from today until life's end.

115
00:11:13,986 --> 00:11:19,193
Very successful, huh?

116
00:11:19,274 --> 00:11:22,317
So let's just look at this, the main thing that he says.

117
00:11:24,240 --> 00:11:26,703
So the first one he says is don't believe anything.

118
00:11:27,524 --> 00:11:28,666
Don't believe anything.

119
00:11:29,648 --> 00:11:33,832
Just because it comes from these things that are established

120
00:11:34,116 --> 00:11:59,888
by scriptural authorities or something coming from the past so oral tradition lineage of the teacher here saying collection of texts so fundamentalists might be described as people who believe that the texts are infallible that they are true records and that they have to be entirely and fully believed you know so my

121
00:12:00,424 --> 00:12:05,230
My brother-in-law believes that the whole of the Bible is the word of God, full stop.

122
00:12:06,611 --> 00:12:14,100
And you'll find people in the East who believe that all the scriptures is actually the word of the Buddha, I mean the direct word of the Buddha.

123
00:12:14,822 --> 00:12:28,879
Sometimes you can get the flavor of the Buddha's teaching coming through, but to say, you know, to make a statement that it's the actual words he spoke was, but it gives them a sort of assurance that, you know, it must be right.

124
00:12:29,652 --> 00:12:34,619
Of course they don't recognise that the way they read it is their own interpretation.

125
00:12:35,640 --> 00:12:39,706
Putting that aside, they just take it for real.

126
00:12:41,509 --> 00:12:43,413
Then there are the four rational grounds.

127
00:12:44,453 --> 00:12:52,105
Logic, inferential reasoning and reasoned connotation and the acceptance of views after pondering upon it.

128
00:12:52,826 --> 00:12:56,993
Now most people would think that if they'd thought something through it must necessarily be true.

129
00:12:58,576 --> 00:13:04,865
But we know from the history of our own rationality that it can lead you in a very strange place.

130
00:13:05,885 --> 00:13:23,530
I mean, our 18th century enlightenment, which was about rationality, and probably its greatest product was the Declaration of Human Rights, also produced communism and Nazism, which were very rational doctrines.

131
00:13:24,673 --> 00:13:27,537
Remember, all rationality has to be based on a premise.

132
00:13:28,174 --> 00:13:30,839
And if the premise is wrong, then you're going to end up somewhere else.

133
00:13:34,604 --> 00:13:39,450
A lot of people would believe that just because they've thought something through and it must be therefore right.

134
00:13:41,413 --> 00:13:42,234
It's a dangerous one, eh?

135
00:13:44,376 --> 00:13:52,908
And then there are those on authoritative persons, the impressive speakers and the respected teachers.

136
00:13:53,428 --> 00:13:55,532
So we've had the sad death of

137
00:13:56,203 --> 00:13:57,024
Maybe that, yeah.

138
00:13:58,727 --> 00:14:01,552
I was just reading some of the responses.

139
00:14:02,052 --> 00:14:02,953
It's unbelievable, actually.

140
00:14:03,595 --> 00:14:05,277
It's as bad as it was when she was there.

141
00:14:07,139 --> 00:14:09,082
Sort of the opposing views.

142
00:14:10,104 --> 00:14:18,076
And, you know, you just don't believe somebody because they have authority.

143
00:14:18,616 --> 00:14:24,085
So now you've got this real problem of how do you

144
00:14:24,418 --> 00:14:27,581
how do you find out whether something is true or not?

145
00:14:27,601 --> 00:14:36,172
Then on top of that, you've got the post-modern understanding that all our truths are completely relative to the individual person.

146
00:14:36,692 --> 00:14:41,057
So whatever's true for you, well, it might be true for you, but it's not true for me.

147
00:14:42,197 --> 00:14:52,889
So you have a sort of, these three ways of trying to decide for ourselves as to what's true, what's given to us from traditions,

148
00:14:53,326 --> 00:15:21,325
what we can think about and rationalize with others and come to some sort of understanding and what's true for me so the Buddha simply says well go back to your experience and that's why he talks about something which is so concrete as greed hatred and delusion and he asks you well you know does this create harm or not so he's always going back to direct experience

149
00:15:21,625 --> 00:15:30,332
and to using that as a basis for our understanding of what truth is.

150
00:15:31,173 --> 00:15:39,701
So remember that when he died, when he was dying, Ananda asks him, are you going to leave somebody, you know, to lead us?

151
00:15:40,062 --> 00:15:40,621
And he says, no.

152
00:15:40,802 --> 00:15:45,746
He said, take the Dharma, the teaching, as your light, as your lamp.

153
00:15:46,268 --> 00:15:49,811
Take yourself as the lamp.

154
00:15:49,831 --> 00:15:49,910
See?

155
00:15:50,312 --> 00:15:55,921
So the Dharma, of course, is the tradition and all that, and the logic and all that sort of stuff.

156
00:15:56,361 --> 00:15:58,784
But eventually, I'm afraid it's us.

157
00:15:59,025 --> 00:16:00,927
And if we get it wrong, it's only us that suffer.

158
00:16:01,509 --> 00:16:10,682
So it's a very important point for us to think about.

159
00:16:11,222 --> 00:16:12,745
How do we know something is true?

160
00:16:13,506 --> 00:16:14,548
How do we know something is true?

161
00:16:17,481 --> 00:16:20,508
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

162
00:16:20,788 --> 00:16:33,971
May you, by your investigation of this, arrive at that place of utter happiness sooner rather than later.

